DATA VISUALIZATION ANALYSIS¶

What is the Rating Distribution for the Books?¶

In [13]:
# Ratings Distribution


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12,8))
sns.kdeplot(amz_df['User Rating'], shade = True, ax = ax)
ax.set_xlabel('Rating')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')
ax.set_title('Rating Distribution')
fig.show()
  • Most of the ratings for bestselling books are in the range of 4.5 - 4.9
  • The peak of the ratings is at about 4.75

What is the Genre Distribution for the Books?¶

In [14]:
# Genre Distribution

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12,8))

ax.pie(amz_df['Genre'].value_counts(), autopct = '%1.2f%%', labels = amz_df['Genre'].value_counts().index)
ax.set_title('Genre Distribution')
Out[14]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Genre Distribution')
  • Non-Fiction books are more popular, although the difference is not too substantial

What is the Price Distribuition for the Books?¶

In [15]:
# Price Distribution

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12,8))
sns.histplot(x = 'Price', hue = 'Genre', data = amz_df, ax = ax)
ax.set_xlabel('Price')
ax.set_ylabel('Counts')
ax.set_title('Price Distribution')
fig.show()
  • Most of the books of both the genres are present between the range of 0€ - 22€

Is there a Price Difference Between Two Genres?¶

In [16]:
most_expensive_book = amz_df.loc[amz_df.Price > 100]
median_vals = amz_df.groupby('Genre').median()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))

sns.boxplot(x = "Genre", y = "Price", data = amz_df, ax = ax)
ax.set_yscale('Log')
ax.set_ylabel('Price (Log Scale)')
ax.set_xlabel('Genre Type')
ax.set_title('Price per Genre')
fig.show()
  • Non Fiction books tend to be a more expensive
  • Median for Non Fiction books is 12€, 9€ for Fiction
  • Both have outliers that lie above the max whisker, and there is one bestseller that costs more than 100€ in the Non Fiction section

What is the Price Variation Through Time?¶

In [21]:
# Price Variation through the Time

amz_df.groupby('Year')['Price'].sum().plot(marker = 'o', c = 'g')
plt.title('Variation of Price Over the Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Price')
Out[21]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Price')
  • Before 2010 the prices were at its peak and in 2010 there was a drop.
  • There was a rise till 2012 with a steep decline from 2014 to 2015.
  • There was a significant rise in 2016, but after that onwards there has been a steady decline in the prices.

What Were the Best Books over the Decade?¶

In [22]:
best_books = amz_df['Name'].value_counts()[:10]

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))
sns.barplot(y=best_books.index, x=best_books, ax=ax)
ax.set_xlabel('None')
ax.set_title('Top 10 Bestselling Books from 2009-2019')
fig.show()
  • The Best Book over the Decade was 'Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association, 6th Edition'

What Are the Most Expensive Books?¶

In [27]:
# Most Expensive Books

top_expensive = amz_df.drop(amz_df[amz_df['Price'] < 1].index).sort_values('Price', ascending = False).head(10)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12,8))
sns.barplot(y = top_expensive['Name'], x = top_expensive['Price'], ax = ax)
ax.set_xlabel(None)
ax.set_ylabel(None)
ax.set_title('Expensive books in the Amazon Bestseller List')
fig.show()
  • The most expensive book is 'Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders' and costs about 105€

Who Are the Most Popular Authors?¶

In [30]:
best_author = amz_df[['Name', 'Author']].groupby('Author').agg('nunique').nlargest(10, columns='Name')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (12,8))
sns.barplot(x = best_author.Name, y = best_author.index, ax = ax)  
ax.set_xlabel(None)
ax.set_ylabel(None)
ax.set_title('Author with most Bestselling Books from 2009-2019')
fig.show()
  • The most popular author is Jeff Kinney with 12 Bestselling Books, followed by Rick Riordan with 8 Bestselling Books.
